INSERT INTO weekly_summaries(user_id, week, summary, created_at)
VALUES
  ('a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890', 1, 'This week, you''ve made a strong start, but it''s been a bit of a rollercoaster ride. You''ve stayed consistent with your habits overall, but there have been some dips in mood mid-week. Specifically, day 3 saw your mood drop to 3, and while you were able to push through and complete your indoor workout, you mentioned feeling guilty about missing your outdoor walk. Thankfully, you were able to recover and finish the week strongly.\n\nYour goals have been showing up in your next_day_focus entries, and many of them have paid off. You successfully implemented your plan to set the alarm 15 minutes earlier on day 2, and your diet slipped back on day 6, but you were able to cook a batch of emergency meals for next time. You''ve also had some great days, like day 4 when you felt high energy all day and completed your outdoor run effortlessly.\n\nTo build on your progress, let''s focus on a few areas next week. One thing to work on is handling mid-week slumps - your mood dropped on day 3, and while you recovered, it''s worth exploring strategies to prevent this in the future. Try incorporating some relaxation techniques, like deep breathing or meditation, into your daily routine to help manage stress. Another area to focus on is planning for social events - you mentioned feeling awkward about sticking to your diet at a social event earlier in the week. Try to plan your meals or snacks ahead of time when you know you''ll be going out, and see if that helps you feel more in control. Finally, let''s work on building momentum on your high-energy days - your next_day_focus entry for day 4 had some great advice about using those days to build momentum, not coast. See if you can apply that principle to your daily habits next week.', '2026-03-20T01:02:24.445Z'),
('a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890', 2, 'This week showed a mix of consistent progress and minor setbacks. You maintained a strong streak through days 8-11, with daily workouts, clean diet, and steady reading. However, your mood took a dip on day 9, which carried over to day 12. It''s interesting that your next-day focus entries often turned into actual achievements the next day - for instance, day 9''s focus on blocking workout time paid off on day 10.\n\nNotable wins from the week include reaching the two-week milestone (Day 10), noticing visible improvements in physique and sleep quality (Day 14), and pushing through cravings to stay on diet (Day 11). You also successfully navigated social pressure to drink at a gathering (Day 13).\n\nTo build on this momentum, let''s focus on a few areas for improvement next week. High-mood days often correlate with consistent sleep (noted on Day 12 and Day 14), so prioritizing 7 hours of sleep each night should be a top priority - try going to bed 30 minutes earlier to see if that makes a difference. Additionally, your body is starting to adapt to the routine, but minor knee discomfort on day 14 suggests you might need to revisit stretching before outdoor workouts. Finally, your mind-wandering challenge (Day 8) and missed indoor workout (Day 9) indicate that finding ways to stay focused, especially on reading, should be a focus for next week - consider reading during a quiet morning hour.', '2026-03-20T01:03:27.496Z'),
('a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890', 3, 'This week has seen you steadily build on your momentum, with a strong streak of consistent habits and a notable increase in physical performance. Your mood ratings have remained relatively stable, with a slight dip mid-week but a swift recovery by the weekend. It''s also great to see that your next-day focus entries have been translating into tangible achievements the following day, demonstrating your growing self-awareness and proactive approach to improvement.\n\nOne of the standout moments from the week was day 16, when you pushed through a tough outdoor run in the rain and felt empowered afterwards. This kind of mental toughness is exactly what you''ve been building towards, and it''s fantastic to see you drawing on that inner strength. Another highlight was day 20, where you achieved a personal best with visible muscle definition and a faster running pace. This is a testament to your hard work and dedication to your goals. Finally, I want to acknowledge the resilience you showed on day 17, when a low mood made everything harder but you still managed to complete all your tasks.\n\nAs we move forward, I''d like to draw your attention to a few areas that may benefit from some focus. Hunger was a recurring challenge for you this week, and you may want to explore adjusting your macros to better manage your energy needs on high-output days -> Try tracking your calorie intake for a few days to identify patterns and see if any adjustments can be made. Additionally, you''ve been struggling with low mood on certain days, and it may be worth experimenting with different strategies to boost your mood, such as a short morning walk or some gentle stretching -> Try incorporating a 10-minute morning walk into your routine to see if it has a positive impact on your mood. Finally, you''ve been consistently completing all your tasks on time, but you may want to explore ways to make your workouts feel less sluggish, such as incorporating more variety in your exercise routine -> Try mixing up your workout routine by adding some new exercises or incorporating different types of exercise, such as', '2026-03-20T01:04:07.965Z'),
('a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890', 4, 'This week, you''ve maintained a consistent streak, adhering to your diet and completing both outdoor and indoor workouts every day. However, your mood ratings reveal a slight dip mid-week, with day 23 being the lowest at 3. It''s also worth noting that your next-day focus entries have been showing up as actual achievements the following day, which is a great sign of follow-through. Despite a few challenges, you''ve managed to stay on track and even reached a significant milestone on day 25.\n\nYour standout achievements this week include reaching the 25-day milestone, maintaining momentum post-milestone, and discovering a new running route for your outdoor workouts. You''ve also demonstrated discipline by resisting the temptation to celebrate with a cheat meal and catching a sloppy diet choice early on. Additionally, your ability to adapt and stay focused, as seen in your next-day focus entries, is a testament to your growth.\n\nAs you move forward, there are a few areas to focus on. Firstly, observe that your mood ratings have been consistently high on days 24 and 25, but dipped on day 28. -> Try to introduce small novelty elements, like new music or a walking path, to combat boredom. Secondly, while your diet has been perfect, you mentioned feeling mechanical about the routine on day 28. -> Experiment with a new recipe or cooking technique to add some variety. Lastly, you''ve been reading consistently, but mentioned feeling like it was a chore on day 27. -> Switch book genres temporarily if current book loses engagement.', '2026-03-20T01:04:38.886Z'),
('a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890', 5, 'This week had its ups and downs, but you maintained a remarkable level of consistency across all habits despite a few minor setbacks. Your mood rating started strong at 4 on day 29, dipped slightly on day 32, but recovered nicely by day 35. It''s great to see that your next-day-focus entries from day 29 and 31 have actually contributed to your achievements the following day, especially your focus on shifting your last meal to avoid hunger spikes.\n\nThe highlights of this week include your impressive endurance through a cold, pushing through carefully and still managing to complete your indoor workout on day 31. You also successfully returned to full outdoor routine on day 33, feeling back to 100 percent. Additionally, your mental reset after losing two days of full output was a testament to your resilience, and you''ve now crossed the halfway mark to silver. Lastly, your confidence is up, and your posture has improved noticeably.\n\nHowever, there are a few areas that require attention next week. Your hunger spikes in late evening are becoming a regular pattern -> try reducing your last meal by 30 minutes to 1 hour to see if that helps. Your slight feelings of isolation after skipping a social event on day 34 -> explore one way to socialise that fits within the program, even if it''s just a quick coffee break with a friend. Additionally, your mild DOMS in legs on day 35 -> add foam rolling session before bed on heavy leg days to help with recovery.', '2026-03-20T01:05:03.090Z'),
('a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890', 6, 'You''ve completed another week, and it''s been a solid one. Mood ratings have held steady between 3 and 5, with a dip on day 38, but you bounced back well. Notably, you''ve consistently followed through on your next-day focus entries, using them to drive real changes in your habits. For example, you used the app you mentioned on day 36 to pace yourself better, and on day 37, you left your phone outside the workout space as you''d planned.\n\nSome standout moments this week include setting a personal best on your morning run on day 36, reading a chapter that genuinely changed your perspective on day 37, and completing everything despite a low-energy day on day 38. It''s also great to see you reflecting on the process and planning ahead, like identifying the triggers behind your cravings on day 39 and starting to think about what habits to keep after day 75 on day 40. Those next-day focus entries are paying off.\n\nAs we move forward, let''s keep an eye on a few areas. It seems like day 38 was a low point for your energy, so consider scheduling workouts for morning whenever possible to see if that helps. Also, be aware that cravings for junk food are intensifying, and it might be worth exploring what''s driving those feelings. Finally, you''ve mentioned a slight plateau in visible progress, but it''s essential to remember that plateaus are normal – trust the process and stay consistent.', '2026-03-20T01:05:41.769Z'),
('a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890', 7, 'You''ve had a strong week overall, with a consistent streak of daily habits across all 7 days. This is a testament to your hard work and dedication to the 75 Hard challenge. However, you did experience a dip in mood on day 44, but quickly bounced back on day 45 with a renewed focus on processing setbacks and redirecting your energy. It''s also notable that your next_day_focus entries have been directly linked to your achievements on the following day, which is a great pattern to continue.\n\nYour highlights of the week include a particularly strong day 46, where you achieved your best outdoor run of the challenge and felt completely in flow. You also had a significant achievement on day 45, getting back on track and re-establishing a strong routine. Additionally, you''ve made great progress on your workouts, with visible abs appearing for the first time on day 48, and you''re now just one day away from reaching the silver milestone.\n\nYour focus areas for next week include addressing the slight anxiety you felt on day 49 about the final 25 days being harder. This is a normal concern, but try to approach each day with a clear focus on the present moment, rather than worrying about what''s ahead. You may also want to explore ways to increase the intensity of your workouts, as you mentioned wanting to push beyond your comfort zone. Finally, since your mood has been consistently high, try to use the energy to tackle any challenges that come your way, rather than waiting for motivation to strike.', '2026-03-20T01:06:21.085Z'),
('a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890', 8, 'This week was a strong foundation for the final push, with a slight dip in mood on day 53 due to external circumstances. You maintained an impressive streak of daily workouts and habits, and your reflection on emotional moments shows growth and awareness. Unfortunately, your next day focus entries sometimes didn''t translate into immediate achievements, which can be a pattern to work on.\n\nOne of the highlights this week was day 51, where you achieved a silver milestone and reported feeling energized, marking a significant shift in mindset. On day 55, you demonstrated resilience and bounced back from a tough emotional day, showcasing your growing capacity for resilience. Additionally, your achievements on days 51 and 55 suggest that you''re developing a stronger identity centered around discipline and progress.\n\nLet''s focus on a few areas to work on next week: \nEmotional moments becoming more frequent -> Try to acknowledge and accept emotions as valid, without letting them dictate choices, and remind yourself that you''ve overcome them before.\nMood rating consistently below 5 -> Take a 5-minute morning walk outside, even if it''s just around the block, to get some sunlight and fresh air.\nNext day focus often not translating into action -> Write down the specific actions you''ll take the next day, and prioritize the most important ones to ensure consistency.\nBoredom with indoor workouts -> Experiment with new exercises or workout routines to add variety and keep your mind engaged.\nCoasting towards the finish -> Focus on making the next 20 days the strongest weeks of the challenge, rather than taking things easy.', '2026-03-20T01:06:46.582Z'),
('a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890', 9, 'You''ve had a consistent week, with every single day meeting your diet and workout goals. Your mood ratings have been steady, hovering around a 4, which is a great place to be. Notably, you''ve been following through on your next-day focus entries, which suggests you''re developing a strong habit of reflection and planning. However, your mood didn''t dip this week, so it''s worth paying attention to how you handle potential setbacks in the future.\n\nYour wins this week include successfully adapting to new indoor exercises, achieving a high level of diet compliance, and pushing through a challenging workout despite feeling impatient. You''ve also started to think about post-75 Hard maintenance routines, which is a great sign of forward thinking. Additionally, you''ve found ways to enjoy cold-weather running, which shows your flexibility and resilience.\n\nOne area to focus on next week is your challenge of choosing the next book to read. You''ve noticed this challenge before, and it''s worth developing a strategy to make it easier. -> Consider making a list of book recommendations or authors you''d like to read, so you have a clear direction for your next choice. Another area to focus on is your potential loneliness. You''ve mentioned this challenge before, and it''s worth exploring ways to connect with others who are going through similar experiences. -> Consider joining an online community or finding a workout buddy to share your journey with.', '2026-03-20T01:07:13.209Z'),
('a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890', 10, 'You had a consistent week with a mix of high and low mood days, but overall you stayed on track with your habits. Your mood dipped slightly to 4 on days 67 and 68, but you bounced back to 5 on day 70. It''s also worth noting that your next day focus entries from days 65 and 66 showed up as achievements the following days, demonstrating your ability to follow through on your intentions.\n\nThe highlights from this week are your consistent adherence to your habits, with every day marked as a success. You also showed impressive clarity and focus, with no challenges reported on day 65 and a strong sense of determination on day 70. Additionally, your achievements included making progress on your book and completing your workouts with a personal best on day 67.\n\nYour focus areas for next week should be to stay grounded and avoid overconfidence. You can try breaking down the emotional weight of the end approaching into smaller, more manageable tasks, and prioritize self-care to avoid burnout.', '2026-03-20T01:07:49.932Z');
